          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter>
            <html:p>A function <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f\colon  A \to  B]]></fr:tex> is called <html:em><html:strong><html:span style="white-space: nowrap"><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[n]]></fr:tex>-truncated</html:span></html:strong></html:em> when all of its <fr:link href="https://www.jonmsterling.com/foreign/erct/erct-001Q.xml" title="Fiber" addr="forest://erct/erct-001Q" type="local">fibers</fr:link> are <fr:link href="https://www.jonmsterling.com/foreign/erct/erct-001G.xml" title="n-truncated type" addr="forest://erct/erct-001G" type="local"><html:span style="white-space: nowrap"><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[n]]></fr:tex>-truncated</html:span> types</fr:link>. By analogy, we shall also refer to maps as <html:em><html:strong>contractible</html:strong></html:em> when their fibers are; we shall refer to maps as <html:em><html:strong>propositional</html:strong></html:em> when their fibers are <fr:link href="https://www.jonmsterling.com/foreign/erct/erct-001I.xml" title="Proposition" addr="forest://erct/erct-001I" type="local">propositions</fr:link>.</html:p>
